Let me offer you something I think you'll enjoy more: an excerpt from a work in progress of mine about fishing and sensory processing disorders, from a chapter titled "The Cost Of Fishing". Straight ahead descriptive prose: a fisherman has just landed a huge native brook trout in a New Hampshire stream: "The fish is an improbable amalgam of contrasts: simplicity and complexity at war, subtlety and flash colliding, opposing colors vying for space on the canvas of its flanks, and layer upon layer of hues and patterns struggling to assert themselves over one another. The effect is at once jarring yet sublime, a dizzying and hallucinogenic explosion of color superimposed on restful earth tones and mild sunrises. It is dazzle camouflage done to perfection. Most arresting are its spots, some like random yellow bursts of fireworks exploding against a night sky, and others suggesting more intent, as if an artist had somehow flicked a brush-load of droplets along the lateral line without hitting it. Each droplet holds a crimson center, a sharp red bull’s-eye surrounded by a thin sky-blue ring that shades away from the center through periwinkle into deep purple before it disappears. He is no more able to comprehend what he sees than a child gazing into the movement of a fine watch. He fumbles in the face of its complications, unable to grasp its intricacies and mechanisms. Hefting the fish critically, and inchworm-spanning one hand from nose to tail, a pair of conclusions is reached: nearly 18 inches, and just under 3 pounds. This information is distilled even further, down to a pair of four-letter words: nice fish." ROTFLMAO,"Hot-cha-cha-cha-cha, I gotta a millyun of 'em"....personalities and styles, that is.
